However, we know f is a quasi-isomorphism. Therefore the boundary maps are all isomorphisms. So by exactness of the sequence, H_n (\operatorname {Cone}(f)) must all be zero. But this means \operatorname {Cone}(f) is an acyclic complex, and therefore a projective resolution of 0. Since projective resolutions are unique up to chain homotopy, we have a chain homotopy from \operatorname {Cone}(f) to 0. Throwing away the trivial components, we get a degree 1 map h_n : \operatorname {Cone}_n (f) \to  \operatorname {Cone}_{n+1} (f) such that d_{n+1} h_n + h_{n-1} d_n = 1. Writing it down in components, we have
    \begin {aligned}       h_n^{CC} &: C_{n-1} \to  C_n \\       h_n^{CD} &: C_{n-1} \to  D_{n+1} \\       h_n^{DC} &: D_n \to  C_n \\       h_n^{DD} &: D_n \to  D_{n+1} \\     \end {aligned}
    such that
    \begin {aligned}       h_n^{CC} d^C_n + d^C_{n+1} h_{n+1}^{CC} + 1 &= h^{DC}_n f_{n} \\       d^C_n h^{DC}_n &= h^{DC}_n d^D_{n+1} \\       f_n h^{CC}_n + d^D_{n+1} h^{CD}_n + h_n^{DD} f_n &= h^{CD}_n d^C_n \\       f_n h^{DC}_n + d^D_{n+1} h^{DD}_n + h^{DD}_n d^D_{n+1} &= 1.     \end {aligned}
    The second equation shows that h^{DC}_\bullet  forms a chain map. The first and fourth equation then shows that h^{DC} f and f h^{DC} are homotopic to the identity, respectively, with homotopies given by h^{CC} and h^{DD}. Therefore f has a homotopy inverse.

Another way to see this is to let \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}^\textrm {op} \dashv  \operatorname {¿}, where \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}^\textrm {op} : \mathsf {Set} \to  (\mathsf {Set} \to  \mathsf {Set})^\textrm {op} is the coyoneda embedding, and calculate
    \begin {aligned}       \operatorname {¿}(F) &= \hom (1, \operatorname {¿}(F)) \\       &= \hom _{\mathsf {Set} \to  \mathsf {Set}} (F, \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}} (1^\textrm {op})) \\       &= \hom (F, \textrm {Id}).     \end {aligned}
    So we only need to prove the natural transformations FX \to  X form a small set, which works the same way, by substituting X by the powerset of 1.

We need to show that \operatorname {wave}(Y, X) is a small set. Let Y^* be the functor sending a presheaf F to the set F(Y). The right Kan extension is given by
    \begin {aligned}       Y_* (A)(B) &= \hom (\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}} (B), Y_* (A)) \\       &= \hom (Y^* (\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}} (B)), A) \\       &= \hom (\hom (Y, B), A) = A^{B^Y}.     \end {aligned}
    Using the fact that \mathsf {Set} is total and cototal and writing \operatorname {¿} as the witness of cototality, we calculate
    \begin {aligned}       \operatorname {wave}(Y, X) &= \hom _{\mathsf {Psh}(\mathcal {C}) \to  \mathsf {Set}} (\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}} (X^\textrm {op}) \mathbin {\circ } \operatorname {?}, Y^*) \\       &= \hom _{\mathsf {Set} \to  \mathsf {Set}} (\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}} (X^\textrm {op}) \mathbin {\circ } \operatorname {?} \mathbin {\circ } Y_*, \textrm {Id}) \\       &= \hom _{\mathsf {Set} \to  \mathsf {Set}} (\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}} (X^\textrm {op}) \mathbin {\circ } \operatorname {?} \mathbin {\circ } Y_*, \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}} (1^\textrm {op})) \\       &= \hom _{\mathsf {Set}} (1, \operatorname {¿}(\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}} (X^\textrm {op}) \mathbin {\circ } \operatorname {?} \mathbin {\circ } Y_*)) \\       &= \operatorname {¿}(\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}} (X^\textrm {op}) \mathbin {\circ } \operatorname {?} \mathbin {\circ } {Y_*})     \end {aligned}
    where the second equality is because the pseudofunctor (- \to  \mathsf {Set}) preserves adjoint pairs. Hence we know this is a small set.

Given a Hopf algebra H, suppose it is equipped with an element R \in  H \otimes  H, such that
  \begin {aligned}     \tau (\Delta (a)) &= R \Delta (a) R^{-1} \\     (\Delta  \otimes  \textrm {id})(R) &= R_{13} R_{23} \\     (\textrm {id} \otimes  \Delta )(R) &= R_{13} R_{12}   \end {aligned}
  then we call it a braided Hopf algebra. Here \tau  : H \otimes  H \to  H \otimes  H is the twisting map of tensor products, and R_{i j} \in  H^{\otimes  3} is R \otimes  1 with the appropriate factors permuted.

