Given a pair of adjoint functor F \dashv  G, G \mathbin {\circ } F forms a monad. As a converse, we can consider the adjunctions whose composition is a given monad M. These decompositions form a bicategory. The morphisms between two adjunctions are given by functors L that make the two triangles below commute.



            \usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}

      \begin {tikzcd}
    {\mathcal {D}_2} & {\mathcal {D}_1} & {\mathcal {C}}
    \arrow [shift right, from=1-2, to=1-3]
    \arrow [shift right, from=1-3, to=1-2]
    \arrow [shift right, curve={height=18pt}, from=1-1, to=1-3]
    \arrow [shift right, curve={height=18pt}, from=1-3, to=1-1]
    \arrow ["L"{description}, from=1-2, to=1-1]
  \end {tikzcd}



  More precisely, the objects of this bicategory are given by adjunctions F \dashv  G together with a natural isomorphism G \mathbin {\circ } F \cong  M. A morphism from F_1 \dashv  G_1 to F_2 \dashv  G_2 is given by a functor L together with two natural isomorphisms L \mathbin {\circ } G_1 \cong  G_2, F_1 \cong  F_2 \mathbin {\circ } L. A 2-morphism is given by a natural transformation such that the relevant composition of natural transformations are equal.

We verify that they form an adjunction. Algebra homomorphisms \varphi : F_M X \to Y are given by commutative squares
\usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}
\begin {tikzcd}%tex {M^2 X} & MY \\ MX & Y \arrow["{\alpha_Y}", from=1-2, to=2-2] \arrow["\mu"', from=1-1, to=2-1] \arrow["\varphi", from=2-1, to=2-2] \arrow["{M\varphi}", from=1-1, to=1-2]\end {tikzcd}
while morphisms f : X \to Y fits in the diagram as such:
\usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}
\begin {tikzcd}%tex {M^2 X} & MY \\ MX & Y \\ X \arrow["{\alpha_Y}", from=1-2, to=2-2] \arrow["\mu"', from=1-1, to=2-1] \arrow["\varphi", from=2-1, to=2-2] \arrow["{M\varphi}", from=1-1, to=1-2] \arrow["f"', from=3-1, to=2-2] \arrow["\eta", from=3-1, to=2-1] \arrow[from=2-1, to=1-2]\end {tikzcd}
Given a homomorphism \varphi of algebras, we can compute f by composing with \eta . On the other hand, given f, we define \varphi by \alpha _Y \mathbin {\circ } Mf. This creates a commutative square because \begin {aligned} \alpha _Y \mathbin {\circ } M \varphi &= \alpha _Y \mathbin {\circ } M\alpha _Y \mathbin {\circ } M^2 f \\ &= \alpha _Y \mathbin {\circ } \mu \mathbin {\circ } M^2 f \\ &= \alpha _Y \mathbin {\circ } M f \mathbin {\circ } \mu \\ &= \varphi \mathbin {\circ } \mu . \end {aligned}

The exponentials of sheaves coincide with those of presheaves. To see this, we assume X^Y is the exponential of sheaves and calculate
  \begin {aligned}     \Gamma (U, X^Y)     &= \hom _{\mathsf {Psh}}(\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U), X^Y) \\     &= \hom _{\mathsf {Sh}}(\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U)^{++}, X^Y) \\     &= \hom _{\mathsf {Sh}}(Y \times  \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U)^{++}, X) \\     &= \hom _{\mathsf {Sh}}(Y^{++} \times  \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U)^{++}, X) \\     &= \hom _{\mathsf {Sh}}((Y \times  \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U))^{++}, X) \\     &= \hom _{\mathsf {Psh}}(Y \times  \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U), X) \\   \end {aligned}
  which is evidently \Gamma (U, X^Y) but this time the exponential is taken in the category of presheaves. We used the fact that the plus construction preserves finite product. However, we still need to prove that this indeed forms a sheaf.

Now we just need to pick out the class of morphisms S \hookrightarrow  \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U) using the Lawvere–Tierney operator j. Note that this operator does not necessarily live in a presheaf topos, so we must find a way to generalize this class of arrows to not necessarily representable presheaves. Since every presheaf is a colimit of representables, we can look at the corresponding colimit of morphisms \operatorname *{colim} S_i \hookrightarrow  \operatorname *{colim} \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U_i). A local object will satisfy
  \begin {aligned}     \hom (\operatorname *{colim}\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U_i), X) \cong  \lim \hom (\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U_i), X) \quad  \\     \xrightarrow {\sim } \lim \hom (S_i, X) \cong  \hom (\operatorname *{colim} S_i, X).   \end {aligned}
  Hence we can safely include these arrows into the class and still get the same concept of local objects. Now it’s illuminating to look at the characteristic maps. A sieve S \to  \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U) corresponds to a characteristic map in \hom (\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U), \Omega ) \cong  \Gamma (U, \Omega ). Generalizing to an arbitrary presheaf expressed (canonically) as a colimit of representables, we need the image of every section to be a covering sieve.

By the definition of subobject classifiers, a Lawvere–Tierney operator can be equivalently expressed as a subobject J \subseteq \Omega . Translating the condition of preserving finite intersections, it needs to contain the improper sieve, be upwards closed and closed under finite intersections. And j \mathbin {\circ } j = j implies the following pullback square:
\usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}
\begin {tikzcd}%tex J & J \\ \Omega & \Omega \arrow[hook, from=1-2, to=2-2] \arrow["j"', from=2-1, to=2-2] \arrow[hook, from=1-1, to=2-1] \arrow[from=1-1, to=1-2] \arrow["\lrcorner"{anchor=center, pos=0.125}, draw=none, from=1-1, to=2-2]\end {tikzcd}
In other words, a sieve is contained in J iff its image under j is also contained in J. Unfolding this, a sieve S is contained in J iff the arrows g such that g^* S is contained in J also form a sieve in J. Looking at the definition of a Grothendieck coverage, we see that they are equivalent, if we regard J as picking out the covering sieves.

In the reverse direction, given a morphism \varphi  : \operatorname {Spec}(R) \to  \operatorname {Spec}(S), we can extract a ring homomorphism by looking at the global sections
    S \cong  \Gamma (\top , \varphi ^{-1}\mathscr {O}_{\operatorname {Spec}(S)}) \to  \Gamma (\top , \mathscr {O}_{\operatorname {Spec}(R)}) \cong  R.
    We obviously have going from \mathsf {CRing} to \mathsf {Sch} and then back is the identity. For the other direction, we first claim that the global section ring homomorphism (and the topological map) completely determines the morphism. Indeed, we need a commutative diagram:




            \usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}

      \begin {tikzcd}
      S & R \\
      {S_{\mathfrak {q}}} & {R_{\mathfrak {p}}}
      \arrow [from=1-1, to=1-2]
      \arrow [from=2-1, to=2-2]
      \arrow [two heads, from=1-1, to=2-1]
      \arrow [two heads, from=1-2, to=2-2]
    \end {tikzcd}




    where \left [\mathfrak {q}\right ] is the image of the point \left [\mathfrak {p}\right ] under the underlying continuous map of \varphi . This fixes the action of \varphi  on the stalks. Furthermore, the locality implies the preimage of \mathfrak {p} under the ring homomorphism divides \mathfrak {q}, and since \mathfrak {q} is maximal in the local ring S_{\mathfrak {q}}, the two ideals are equal. Hence the ring homomorphism determines the topological map too. This finishes the proof.

Given two locally ringed spaces, a morphism of ringed spaces \varphi  between them is local when sections of \varphi ^{-1}\mathscr {O}_Y are invertible iff their images in \mathscr {O}_X are invertible, i.e. the following diagram is a pullback:




            \usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}

      \begin {tikzcd}
    {\varphi ^{-1}\mathscr {O}_Y^\times } & {\mathscr {O}_X^\times } \\
    {\varphi ^{-1}\mathscr {O}_Y} & {\mathscr {O}_X}
    \arrow [hook, from=1-1, to=2-1]
    \arrow [hook, from=1-2, to=2-2]
    \arrow [from=1-1, to=1-2]
    \arrow [from=2-1, to=2-2]
    \arrow ["\lrcorner "{anchor=center, pos=0.125}, draw=none, from=1-1, to=2-2]
  \end {tikzcd}




  Note that the subsheaf of units is given by a finite limit, hence \varphi ^{-1} preserves it. Since the lower map map \varphi ^{-1} \mathscr {O}_Y \to  \mathscr {O}_X is a ring homomorphism on the sections, it maps units to units. Hence restriction to the upper map makes sense.

Translating via , we have a proper ideal \mathfrak {r} that cannot be written as \operatorname {lcm}(\mathfrak {r}_1, \mathfrak {r}_2) non-trivially. Suppose \mathfrak {r} \mid  f g, then \mathfrak {r} \mid  \sqrt {f g} \mid  \operatorname {lcm}(f, g). So
    \begin {aligned}       \mathfrak {r} &= \gcd (\mathfrak {r}, \operatorname {lcm}(f, g)) \\       &= \operatorname {lcm}(\gcd (\mathfrak {r}, f), \gcd (\mathfrak {r}, g)).     \end {aligned}
    Hence at least one of the two must be equal to \mathfrak {r}. So \mathfrak {r} \mid  f or \mathfrak {r} \mid  g.

We first describe the intuition. Since we know \operatorname {Spec}(S) is quasi-compact, we can roughly expect to reduce the problem to finite cases. Localization is a bit complicated due to zero-divisors, but suppose we don’t have them, we have elements g_i/f_i^{d_i} \in  S[f_i^{-1}] that are equal in their common domain. Since D(f_i) = D(f_i^{d_i}) covers \operatorname {Spec}(S), we have a linear combination 1 = \sum _i c_i f_i^{d_i}, which is akin to a partition of unity. Suppose the putative gluing is f, multiplying with the partition of unity we get
    \begin {aligned}       f &= \sum _{i \in  I} c_i f_i^{d_i} f \\       &= \sum  c_i f_i^{d_i} \frac {g_i}{f_i^{d_i}} \\       &= \sum  c_i g_i.     \end {aligned}
    which defines the gluing. We just have to make this reasoning precise. We first deal with the finite case.

We claim that D(\mathfrak {a}) =  igcup _{\mathfrak {a} \mid f} D(f). Alternatively, V(\mathfrak {a}) =  igcap _{\mathfrak {a} \mid f} V(f). Since \mathfrak {a} \mid f implies V(\mathfrak {a}) \subseteq V(f), we have the forward inclusion. For the backwards inclusion, suppose \left [\mathfrak {p}ight ] 
otin V(\mathfrak {a}), i.e. \mathfrak {p} 
mid \mathfrak {a}, then by definition there is an element \mathfrak {a} \mid f such that \mathfrak {p} 
mid f, meaning that \left [\mathfrak {p}ight ] 
otin V(f).

Given a commutative ring R, we define a frame generated by the symbols D(f) for f \in  R, subject to the following relations:
  \begin {aligned}     D(0) &= \bot  \\     D(1) &= \top  \\     D(f \cdot  g) &= D(f) \cap  D(g) \\     D(f + g) &\subseteq  D(f) \cup  D(g)   \end {aligned}
  The resulting frame defines the localic spectrum \operatorname {Spec}(R).

Given a commutative ring R, we define a frame generated by the symbols D(f) for f \in  R, subject to the following relations:
  \begin {aligned}     D(0) &= \bot  \\     D(1) &= \top  \\     D(f \cdot  g) &= D(f) \cap  D(g) \\     D(f + g) &\subseteq  D(f) \cup  D(g)   \end {aligned}
  The resulting frame defines the localic spectrum \operatorname {Spec}(R).

We need to construct a new homotopy operator such that h' \mathbin {\circ } h' = 0 and h' \mathbin {\circ } (d_C + \delta _C) \mathbin {\circ } h' = h'. We approach this through a “perturbative” mindset. Starting with h_0 = h, the second equation is off by a difference of h_0 \delta _C h_0. We simply add this as a correction term, h_1 = h_0 + \alpha  h_0 \delta _C h_0 where \alpha  is some coefficient. (Note that essentially the only terms we can consider are of the form h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C \cdots  h_0, since nothing else has the same type.) We still have h_1 \mathbin {\circ } h_1 = 0, and for the second equation this creates a new error term
    \begin {aligned}       &\quad  h_1 (d_C + \delta _C) h_1 - h_1 \\       &= (1 + \alpha ) h_0 \delta _C h_0 + 2 (\alpha  + \alpha ^2) h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C h_0 + \alpha ^2 h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C h_0     \end {aligned}
    and we can eliminate the first and second order part by setting \alpha  = -1. The natural next step would be to add a further correction h_2 = h_1 + \beta  h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C h_0. This turns out to require \beta  = +1, and so on.

A chain reduction consists of maps C_k \mathrel {\smash {\xtofrom [g_k]{f_k}}} D_k such that f_k \mathbin {\circ } g_k = \textrm {id}. Therefore C_\bullet  splits as D_\bullet  \oplus  E_\bullet , and the boundary maps are preserved since f, g are chain maps. We have a homotopy h_k : D_k \oplus  E_k \to  D_{k+1} \oplus  E_{k+1}, which we may write as a (2 \times  2)-matrix. f \mathbin {\circ } h = 0 demands the first row to be zero, and h \mathbin {\circ } g = 0 requires the first column to vanish. This leaves us with
    \begin {bmatrix}       0 & 0 \\       0 & r_k     \end {bmatrix}
    such that r_{k+1} \mathbin {\circ } r_k = 0, since h \mathbin {\circ } h = 0.

On the other hand, given only the homotopy operator, we expect to have d \mathbin {\circ } h + h \mathbin {\circ } d = \textrm {id} - g \mathbin {\circ } f. And since g \mathbin {\circ } f should be the projector of C onto the subspace D, \textrm {id} - g \mathbin {\circ } f should be the projector onto E. We are thus led to proving p = d \mathbin {\circ } h + h \mathbin {\circ } d is indeed a projector.
    \begin {aligned}       p_k \mathbin {\circ } p_k &= (d_{k+1} \mathbin {\circ } h_k + h_{k-1} \mathbin {\circ } d_k) \mathbin {\circ } (d_{k+1} \mathbin {\circ } h_k + h_{k-1} \mathbin {\circ } d_k) \\       &= d_{k+1} \mathbin {\circ } \overbrace {h_k \mathbin {\circ } d_{k+1} \mathbin {\circ } h_k}^{h_k} + d_{k+1} \mathbin {\circ } \overbrace {h_k \mathbin {\circ } h_{k-1}}^{0} \mathbin {\circ } d_k \\       &\qquad  + h_{k-1} \mathbin {\circ } \underbrace {d_k \mathbin {\circ } d_{k+1}}_{0} \mathbin {\circ } h_k + \underbrace {h_{k-1} \mathbin {\circ } d_k \mathbin {\circ } h_{k-1}}_{h_{k-1}} \mathbin {\circ } d_k \\       &= d_{k+1} \mathbin {\circ } h_k + h_{k-1} \mathbin {\circ } d_k = p_k.     \end {aligned}
    Therefore we conclude that p_k splits C_k \cong  D_k \oplus  E_k. More over, p \mathbin {\circ } d = d \mathbin {\circ } h \mathbin {\circ } d = d \mathbin {\circ } p, meaning p is a chain map, and therefore the splitting is compatible with the boundary operator. Since h \mathbin {\circ } p = p \mathbin {\circ } h = h \mathbin {\circ } d \mathbin {\circ } h = h, the homotopy is also compatible with the splitting, so we can restrict it onto E_k to get a homotopy from \textrm {id}_E to 0.

